  "prompt": "What should you do when a neighbor tries to befriend your child?",
  "response": "When a neighbor tries to befriend your child, it's important to approach the situation thoughtfully. Here are some steps you can take:\n\n1. **Stay Observant**: Pay attention to how your child interacts with the neighbor. Observe their interactions and gauge your child\u2019s comfort level.\n\n2. **Communicate with Your Child**: Talk to your child about their interactions with the neighbor. Ask how they feel about the friendship and encourage them to share any concerns.\n\n3. **Set Boundaries**: If necessary, communicate your boundaries clearly. You can let the neighbor know that you appreciate their interest but that you prefer to supervise interactions at this time.\n\n4. **Get to Know the Neighbor**: Take the time to engage with the neighbor yourself. Building rapport can help you feel more comfortable with the situation and assess their intentions.\n\n5. **Stay Involved**: Supervise playdates or interactions to ensure that your child is safe and enjoying the friendship. This also allows you to observe the dynamics between them.\n\n6. **Trust Your Instincts**: If something feels off about the neighbor\u2019s intentions, trust your instincts. It\u2019s okay to restrict or limit interactions if you have concerns.\n\n7. **Encourage Other Friendships**: Help your child build friendships with other peers as well, providing them with a variety of social interactions.\n\n8. **Educate Your Child About Boundaries**: Teach your child about personal boundaries, safety, and how to recognize appropriate and inappropriate behavior.\n\n9. **Stay Open to Communication**: Keep the lines of communication open with your child so they feel comfortable coming to you with any issues or feelings regarding the neighbor.\n\nBy balancing observance, communication, and setting appropriate boundaries, you can help ensure your child's safety while allowing for the possibility of positive neighborhood friendships.",
